<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/882436-sheila"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1625174315i/882436._UX100_CR0,1,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/882436-sheila">Sheila</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    It just occurred to me that Clay's leap was, in actuality, a flash of "intuition" - a purely human trait, something that a computer doesn't have. He t<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    It just occurred to me that Clay's leap was, in actuality, a flash of "intuition" - a purely human trait, something that a computer doesn't have. He took a bunch of loose associations and, in a moment of inspiration, was able to bring them together in his head. <br /><br />I'm not saying it's logical, but it seems to tie in with the point Sloan is trying to make. <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
